> GET UP
You stand up from the stalls.

> LOOK

Quire
The Quire is the heart of monastic worship and the centre of the church. Two stalls face each other across a narrow gap, where the brothers gather to chant the Divine Offices. The high altar rises to the east. The Nave lies west, beyond the rood screen. The Night Stairs ascend to the Dorter, and a hall leads south to the Cloister.

> X ROOD SCREEN
A wooden rood screen separates the Nave from the Quire, dividing the public space from the sacred. A simple carved cross tops the screen---the "rood" that gives it its name. The wood is dark with candle smoke.

> X ROOD CROSS
Simply carved and without ornamentation.

> WEST

Nave
The public space, where villagers stand for Mass weekly. The stone floor is worn smooth by centuries of feet. Detailed stained glass admits pale moonlight. The Quire lies to the east, separated by a screen. A doorway in the north wall leads to the Tower Stairs.

The great door to the west is closed.

> X STAINED GLASS
You remember the first time you saw this glass, on the second day of your novitiate. Unlike some other things in the priory that show sign of decay, these still shine brightly on sunny days. The centre pane, the largest, has a golden hammer labelled "II: LABOR OMNIA VINCIT" ("Work Conquers All"), a reminder of the mission of monks.

> X DOOR
A great oaken door. Carved deeply into its face: EGRESSUS FRUCTUM FERT ("Going out bears fruit"). The door is closed.

You remember Brother Aelred's request to meet him in the gardens after the office.

> OPEN DOOR
You open the great door.

> WEST

Porch
This covered entrance protects the great door from the winds that come across the sea from the east. Villagers used to gather here before services, but the number who do so has been declining for years. 

A covered walkway the brothers call "The Passage" leads south.

The great door is open, revealing the Nave to the east.

> CLOSE DOOR
You close the west door, revealing the carving on this face.

> EXAMINE CARVING
A great oaken door. Carved deeply into its face: 

  NOSTRA DOMINA SPINARUM ("Our Lady of Thorns") 
  FUNDATUM ANNO DOMINI MCLII

Almost two hundred years of wind and rain have worn the letters down. The door is closed.

You should go to the gardens. Brother Aelred will be waiting.

