Necessarium
A narrow stone chamber extending from the Hall. A wooden bench with several latrine holes runs along the east wall, each opening onto the dung pit far below. The smell is overpowering. Cold, foul air rises from the pit below.

> WEST

Hall
A plain corridor connecting the two dorters. Wooden floorboards creak underfoot. There are passages to the north, south, and east. Broad stairs lead down.

> SOUTH

Lay Brothers' Cells
This chamber was built to house the lay brothers, those who serve without taking full vows. The walls are marked with darker patches where other cots once stood, and you can see the worn floorboards where chests were dragged back and forth over the years. Now the room holds only Brother Remigio's single cot and chest, pushed against a far wall. The priory's decline is nowhere more visible than in this emptiness, this quiet room that once held the sounds of simple men at their evening prayers.

The only exit is north to the Hall.

> OPEN REMIGIOS CHEST
You open Brother Remigio's chest, revealing a pilgrim badge.

> X BADGE
A small badge, cheaply cast in pewter but carefully kept. It depicts a figure in a monk's robe: St Francis of Assisi, you think, given the birds around him. The kind of thing sold to pilgrims at a shrine. How it ended up in an English priory, in the chest of a Tuscan lay brother, is a story you will never fully know.

> CLOSE CHEST
You close Brother Remigio's chest.

> NORTH

Hall
A plain corridor connecting the two dorters. Wooden floorboards creak underfoot. There are passages to the north, south, and east. Broad stairs lead down.

> NORTH

Dorter
This great room is used by all the choir monks except Brother Oswald. It could easily provide rest for twenty brothers, but there are only eight cots in here now. Each cot has a chest at its foot for any meagre possessions the brother has. 

A window high up reflects cool morning light on the floor.

A doorway leads south to the Hall. Narrow stairs descend to the Quire, where offices are held.

> DOWN

Night Stairs
Midway on the narrow stone stairway connecting the Dorter to the Quire. These are the Night Stairs: three times each night, monks file down in darkness for Matins, Lauds, and Prime. The walls are close, the air still.

A lone candle flickers in its niche.

From a distance, you can hear the singing continue.

> X CANDLE
A canonical hour candle is used by Brother Cuthbert to tell the hours for offices. It has burned down past 7 marks, leaving 17 marks remaining below the flame. You estimate the time as quarter past seven.

From a distance, you can hear the singing continue.

> WAIT UNTIL 7:55
Time passes.

The singing from the Quire stops.

> DOWN

Quire
The Quire is the heart of monastic worship and the centre of the church. Two stalls face each other across a narrow gap, where the brothers gather to chant the Divine Offices. The high altar rises to the east. The Nave lies west, beyond the rood screen. The Night Stairs ascend to the Dorter, and a hall leads south to the Cloister.

> * Chapels
[Comment recorded]

> EAST

Sanctuary
A domed ceiling rises above this, where Prior Oswald leads public Mass. A chapel is to the east. The Sacristy lies south. A closed gate bars the narrow stairs descending to the Crypt.

You can see the high altar here.

> EAST

Lady Chapel
The largest of the three chapels, dedicated to the Blessed Virgin. This chapel sees more use than the others: the brothers pray here for the priory's patroness, Our Lady of Thorns. To the west is the Sanctuary. Small doorways lead north and south to smaller chapels. 

A statue of Mary stands in a niche and a stone altar is next to her.

> X STATUE
A stone statue of the Blessed Virgin Mary. Her hands are open in a gesture of welcome and mercy. Her carved face is serene.

Carved on the base:

  BEATAE MARIAE MATRIS DEI 
  (Blessed Mary, Mother of God)

> X ALTAR
A simple stone altar, worn by generations of prayer.

> SOUTH

St Jude Chapel
A small chapel dedicated to St Jude, patron of desperate causes. The stone floor is worn down---many desperate souls have visited here over the generations, praying for urgent escape from terrible situations. A doorway leads north to the Lady Chapel. 

A painted statue of the saint is in a corner. Near it is a stone altar with a prayer mat laid before it.

> X STATUE
A wooden statue of St Jude, simply carved and painted. The saint holds a staff in one hand. His painted eyes seem to gaze down at those who kneel before him in desperation.

> X ALTAR
A simple stone altar. Someone has left an offering of small red berries on it.

> X BERRIES
Small seed pods. You don't know them by sight, though---perhaps you might recognise them by a different sense?

Someone carefully gathered these as an offering. They're fresh and fragrant, picked within the last day or two.

> SMELL THEM
A faint, floral scent.

                                                       
